SIMPLE: thrum
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thrum
<hw>Thrum</hw> <pr>(thr⟦ucr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>thrum</ets>, <ets>throm</ets>; akin to OD. <ets>drom</ets>, D.
<ets>dreum</ets>, G. <ets>trumm</ets>, lump, end, fragment, OHG.
<ets>drum</ets> end, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧r⟦oum⟧mr</ets> edge, brim, and L.
<ets>terminus</ets> a limit, term. Cf. <er>Term</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>thrumb</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of
the ends of weaver's threads; hence, any soft, short threads or tufts
resembling these.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any coarse yarn; an unraveled strand of
rope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A threadlike part of a flower; a
stamen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A shove out of place; a small
displacement or fault along a seam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A mat made of canvas and tufts of
yarn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thrum cap</b></col>, <cd>a knitted cap.</cd>
<au>Halliwell.</au> -- <col><b>Thrum hat</b></col>, <cd>a hat made of
coarse woolen cloth.</cd> <au>Minsheu.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thrum
<hw>Thrum</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Thrummed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Thrumming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To furnish with
thrums; to insert tufts in; to fringe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Are we born to <qex>thrum</qex> caps or pick straw?</q>
<rj><qau>Quarles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To insert short pieces of
rope-yarn or spun yarn in; <as>as, to <ex>thrum</ex> a piece of canvas,
or a mat, thus making a rough or tufted surface</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Thrum
<hw>Thrum</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[CF. Icel. <ets><?/ruma</ets> to
rattle, to thunder, and E. <ets>drum</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
play rudely or monotonously on a stringed instrument with the fingers;
to strum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to make a monotonous drumming noise; <as>as,
to <ex>thrum</ex> on a table</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Thrum
<hw>Thrum</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To play, as a stringed
instrument, in a rude or monotonous manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to drum on; to strike in a monotonous manner;
to <xex>thrum</xex> the table.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrum-eyed</ent>⟦br⟧
